[i]Posted: 10 Feb 2023, Rated: 8[/i]

There's a lot to say about [i]Deal with the Devil[/i], because there is so much that has been crammed into this game. This isn't surprising, as sophomore designer [person=75718][/person]'s first effort [i][thing=161970][/thing][/i] had a lot of moving parts including an app as well. The lineage is clear.

I'll start with what the game is known for:

• Blind trading with the other players thanks to the amazing app;
• Social deduction with hidden roles;
• Low to negative scoring due to a punishing (but known) phase;
• Production and point scoring through tableau building.

By the way, "tableau building" should be a recognized mechanism on BGG. Let's make that happen.

When you look at how points are generated and more importantly where you will spend most of your time, here's what the game actually is:

• Production and point scoring through tableau building;
• Low to negative scoring due to a punishing (but known) phase;
• Blind trading with the other players thanks to the amazing app;
• Social deduction with hidden roles.

If those first two items are your cup of tea, then absolutely give [i]Deal with the Devil[/i] a try! The following two items give the game a unique and innovative feel. However, if you don't like either of those first two items (for example, you don't like having to feed your workers -- there are no workers to feed here, nonetheless there are steep consequences for poor planning), then you are going to hate this game.

As for the social deduction element: it isn't a make-or-break part of the game. Even if you know who is the Devil, you may still take their deals. I'll throw in a random TV reference: from 1996 to 1999 there was a TV show named [i][url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0115270/]Millennium[/url][/i] starring [url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0000448/]Lance Henriksen[/url]. One [url=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Somehow,_Satan_Got_Behind_Me]memorable episode[/url] had four elderly men sitting in a coffee shop. They all turn out to be demons, and they're bemoaning the fact that mankind no longer needs to be tempted to be damned. The unimportant, everyday nature of their true identities fits this game perfectly.

I love games that are unforgiving. See anything from [company=140][/company]. I think that Matúš Kotry has a unique design perspective. He worked on this game for [i]seven years[/i]; he's not just dumping the hottest trends into a blender and pouring out a new game every ten months. [i]Deal with the Devil[/i] is a bargain that I am glad to have made.

[i]Posted: 2/8/11, Rated: 7[/i] {2P: ?, 3P: ?, 4P: 7, 5P: ?}
[i]Hansa Teutonica[/i] was the [i][thing=18602]Caylus[/thing][/i] of 2009. What I mean by that analogy is that it received a ton of buzz. The world was going to alter its orbit for [i]Hansa Teutonica[/i] as it had for other supreme buzz-generators. My challenge is that I haven't been impressed with [i][thing=18602]Caylus[/thing][/i]. I know how to play, and I've enjoyed it on [url=http://www.brettspielwelt.de/Spiele/Caylus/]BrettspielWelt[/url], but my face-to-face games have been blasé. How would another buzz-generator fare? The answer is as nuanced as the game itself.
Components-wise, this game is a throwback to the Eurogames of yesteryear. There are a few cardboard tokens, but for the most part there are a lot of wooden cubes and discs. This isn't a bad thing at all, but the spartan nature of these components made me realize how I'd gotten away from games with wooden cubes over the past couple of years!
